<COREF ID="32" TYPE="IDENT">The U.S.</COREF> said <COREF ID="32" TYPE="IDENT">it</COREF> would fully support <COREF ID="19" TYPE="IDENT">the resistance</COREF> -- and did n't .
With <COREF ID="23" TYPE="IDENT">the February 1987 U.N. accords</COREF> `` relating to <COREF ID="21" TYPE="IDENT">Afghanistan</COREF> , '' <COREF ID="16" TYPE="IDENT">the Soviet Union</COREF> got everything <COREF ID="16" TYPE="IDENT">it</COREF> needed to consolidate permanent control .
The terms of <COREF ID="23" TYPE="IDENT">the Geneva accords</COREF> leave <COREF ID="16" TYPE="IDENT">Moscow</COREF> free to provide <COREF ID="16" TYPE="IDENT">its</COREF> clients in <COREF ID="11" TYPE="IDENT">Kabul</COREF> with assistance of any kind -- including the return of Soviet ground forces -- while requiring <COREF ID="32" TYPE="IDENT">the U.S.</COREF> and <COREF ID="6" TYPE="IDENT">Pakistan</COREF> to cut off aid .
